<section class="hero">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="eyebrow">For Families & Beachgoers</p>
    <h1>A beach day should be fun, relaxing, and safe.</h1>
    <p class="lead">Understanding basic water safety helps families enjoy the Great Lakes while reducing risk, especially when conditions change quickly.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container grid grid-3">
    <article class="card">
      <h2>Simple Safety Tips</h2>
      <ul class="feature-list">
        <li>Check the weather, wind, and water conditions before you go.</li>
        <li>Be cautious on windy days or after storms, even if the sun is out.</li>
        <li>Stay well away from piers, breakwalls, and jetties.</li>
        <li>Swim near lifeguards when they are present.</li>
        <li>If conditions do not feel right, choose not to enter the water.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h2>What Parents Should Know</h2>
      <p>Rip currents occur on the Great Lakes and can be difficult to spot. Dangerous currents may exist even when the water looks calm or after a storm passes.</p>
      <p>Children can be pulled into deeper water very quickly. Many emergencies happen close to shore, near structures, or in deeper areas around sandbars.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <h2>Talking to Kids</h2>
      <p>Children do not need scary details. They need clear, simple rules.</p>
      <ul class="feature-list">
        <li>"We check the water conditions before we swim."</li>
        <li>"If the water is rough or the waves are big, we stay out."</li>
        <li>"If you feel tired or pulled away from shore, float and wave for help."</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-muted">
  <div class="container grid grid-2">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Beach Checklist</p>
      <h2>Do not let your first safety check happen in the lake.</h2>
      <p>A few minutes of preparation can prevent a dangerous or deadly situation. Local knowledge can be helpful, but conditions should still be checked before anyone enters the water.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="checklist">
      <h3>Before You Go</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Review the weather and wind forecast.</li>
        <li>Pay attention to wind direction and strength, not just temperature.</li>
        <li>Be extra cautious near piers, breakwalls, and jetties.</li>
        <li>Observe flags, signs, advisories, and closures.</li>
        <li>Decide where you will swim before entering the water.</li>
        <li>Talk with family or friends about what to do if someone is pulled away.</li>
        <li>Call 911 and throw or extend something that floats if someone is in trouble.</li>
        <li>When conditions feel confusing, stay out of the water.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
